attributes.descriptionHtml:
Akita is crate trained.  She knows the word 'crate' and will go to her crate when told.
She will also get in the crate on her own when she sees me getting ready to leave or if there is a lot of commotion.  She feels safe there.
I usually give her a dingo or some other treat when I leave home.
She used to sleep in her crate at night.  She now sleeps in my bed but I think she could easily go back to sleeping in the crate.  Her crate can go with her to her new home.
Akita is not destructive.  She does not chew on shoes, furniture, etc.
But, she will get trash out of the trash can if it is not covered.
She will sit close when you eat, hoping to be given leftovers.  
Don't leave unattended food and expect it to be there when you return to your seat.
She loves other dogs.  She really 'NEEDS' to be with another dog.  She is bored and lonely without a buddy.   Often, out of boredom, she will try to play with the cats.
She loves to run and be outside.  She doesn't get enough outdoor exercise.
She gets along well with cats but will chase them if they run.   She could accidently hurt a kitten because she is unaware of her size and has a herding instinct.  She thinks she is a lap dog and she doesn't know her own strength.  
She can get jealous.  If another pet is given attention, she comes right over to get her share of attention.  She often puts her paw on you.
She will go after thrown sticks, balls and discs but doesn't really bring them back.  She sometimes interferes with kids playing ball because she will take the ball in her mouth and run with it.  
Akita is house trained.  She will ring bells I have on the door knob or bark at the door if she needs to go out or if the cat is outside waiting to come in.
She has never bitten anyone but once she grazed my arm with her tooth because she got excited.  When she gets excited, she will jump around, usually with her mouth open, which is how I got grazed.
She used to have terrible separation anxiety.  She would lick her paws and legs raw. She has been on different anxiety medicines in the past.  She isn't taking any right now since she has been doing well.
She doesn't really like thunderstorms or fireworks.
She does not like to hear yelling.  She will retreat to another room.
She does not like it when anyone throws their arms up in the air.  She gets afraid and will growl and bark.
If you are working at the computer, she will come over and take her strong nose and move your arm when she thinks it is time to pet her.
She loves to go on walks.  She gets excited when she hears the word 'walk' or sees me get her leash.  She knows to 'go potty' in the yard before we start our walk, she never goes in anyone else's yard, then goes again in our yard when we return home.  She loves smelling the other dogs' smells.   But, she is not a trained walker.  She pulls on the leash and darts from one side of our neighborhood road to the other.
She is not happy staying at a boarding kennel, but she did do pretty well the last time she stayed.  Twice, when she was younger,  she came home from the kennel licking her legs and paws.  I stopped using the kennel and left her instead with my sister which Akita loved since my sister had other dogs. I tried the kennel again last year to see how she would do since my sister was unavailable.  Akita had no problems on this last kennel stay.
Akita will not make a good first impression with prospective families .  She barks at strangers when she first meets new people.  When the doorbell rings or she sees someone pull into the driveway, she barks frantically.  She acts ferocious but she is really timid.  She is especially leery of men.  But, after a few minutes of interaction, she will sit in visitors' laps if they let her.  
I believe she would do best in an adult household who is looking for a second dog.   She also needs a yard in which to run.
Akita does not go up or down stairs.  I have not worked with her to overcome that fear because my house does not have stairs.  
She has a benign fatty lump in her belly.  Tidewater Vet evaluated her in Jan 2016 and said it was nothing to worry about.
Akita's last shots were given 7-25-15 (including 3 year rabies).  She takes heartworm preventative monthly and flea preventative during the warm months.  She has been spayed.
She will eat many different brands of dog food.  Akita is content with Purina One.  Sometimes I will buy a Sensitive Skin formula of one of the brands Petco carries because she tends to scratch a lot and I think it helps her scratch less.  I usually give her 1/2-1 can of wet food each morning and leave dry food out throughout the day.  
It is difficult to give her up because I do love her.  I never intended to get a dog, my granddaughter moved in with me and wanted her but she soon lost interest in having a dog.  I am now retired and will be traveling even more.  It isn't fair to keep putting Akita in the kennel especially when she isn't happy there.  
But, most importantly, Akita needs to be in a home with another dog.  She seems lonely for the company of another dog.  I really think she would be happier with another canine companion.
I will keep her until a good home is found.  I will also take her back if the home does not work out until another can good fit can be found.  I think she would be stressed to bounce from home to home.

attributes.descriptionHtml:
Asha, formerly known as Sasha, was transferred to her ARF Foster home from the Tri-County Shelter when she was about 6 weeks pregnant.  Her pups were born on 1/31 - 2/1/2-21.

Asha is a nice dog.  She is housebroken and enjoys being in the same room with you.  She's happy to lay at your feet, and walks nicely on a halt-lead.  She is smart - so smart, she can open cans of dog food... or get into the garbage.  So, she needs a care-giver who will put her brain to more positive uses.  

She is good around cats, and just ignores them. She is in a foster home with two other dogs, and is fine, however, she is not trustworthy around ALL dogs.  A slow, neutral, introduction will be needed.  She is wary of strangers at first, but within 10 minutes and lots of treats, she becomes quite friendly.

Asha has most likely spent all of her life being a momma.  She isn't sure how to play, but certainly knows how to love.

A DNA Test was done on Asha's pup, Lila.  The results show American Pit Bull Terrier, Labrador, American Eskimo and Poodle, among a few other breeds.  According to Embark, Poodles will also pass on the wire-hare gene.

attributes.descriptionHtml: Due to a lack of time, 2 other dogs and a new baby, we are trying to Bandit another home that can comfort him and spend time with him to exert some of his energy. Bandit is energetic , loving and caring. He is very loyal and a great watch dog - in fact he even alerted us during a time when our home was being broken into. For that fact alone, we know he loves us and would make a great pet to any loving family. Bandit has been through obedience classes and knows the 10 basic commands. He is great with kids and people and greets them all with open arms. We even have to calm him down after the excitement of meeting new people. Bandit enjoys car rides and also likes to go for walks, but prefers to be inside with his family. We would like to see Bandit go to a good stable home where he can get the attention and exercise he deserves and needs. If you are looking for a good companion in life, we think you should come meet Bandit!! We love Bandit very much but feel it is only fair to him and to our household to have him in another home where he can get better loving care. Bandit is slender and in great health. He recently had his teeth cleaned and all of his shots are up to date. For pictures please visit: http://www.magsr.org/maleadopt.htm#bandit. For more information or any questions please call Tania at 301-866-0816.

attributes.descriptionHtml:
Benson was given up with another dog by a family who was "moving and couldn't take the dogs with them."  He's the average "Terrier Mix," but he looks like a cross between a Puggle (beagle/pug) and a Schnauzer, so let's have fun and call him a SCHNUGGLE!!

Benson is a skilled hugger and kisser.  He literally wraps his paws around your neck and squeezes!  He is all about love and is happiest when he's right beside you.  He's more housebroken than most, and knows how to SIT like a pro.  He's a nice size where he's easy to handle but far from fragile. 

Benson is fine with the other dogs in his foster home, but hasn't decided he want's to dive into playing quite yet.  He lingers back, and likes his personal space.  He seems to like watching the other dogs as they chase each other around the living room.  He is curious about toys, but doesn't know exactly what to do with them.  I think, in time, he'll come out of his shell and find the joys of really being a dog.  He chases the cat, but will quit with a stern, "NO, LEAVE IT!"  

Benson wants to sit on your lap or crawl up on the top of the couch behind you as you watch your favorite show.  He's eager to please, and could probably learn a few tricks without much problem.  Benson IS a bit protective of himself though.  He doesn't like to be pulled by his collar, and isn't fond of having his feet touched. He will come when called, and is thrilled when he can be rewarded with a snuggle and a pat.  He's just a fellow who prefers an invitation rather than a demand.

Just to be safe, we'd prefer he go to a home with a family who is patient and mature enough to enjoy all Benson has to offer, but who can respect his personal space.  Younger kids would not be ready for him yet.

attributes.descriptionHtml:
Big Country has an unknown history, but it may not have been a pleasent one.  At some point in his young life, he sustained a substantial hip injury that was never treated.  The traumatic event, however, did not impact his personality.  This boy is ALL LOVE.  He has a wondereful nature, and loves to play, go for gentle walks and lay at your feet.  He's smart and knows a few commands.  He loves his canine companions.  He's curious about the cat, is excited by birds and squirrels, and is determined to find the toad in the backyard that continues to elude him.

Country has a long life ahead of him.  He will become a treasured companion.  BUT... in a couple years he may need surgery on his left hip.  ARF has consulted with local vets and a surgeon to understand the severity of his injury.  Though his hip is fractured, it has healed with scar tissue that has allowed him near normal mobility.  He may never have additional issues, but it is possible that without surgery, arthritis and muscle deterioation will occur, and he will live with terrible pain. 

Big Country will need a dedicated and financially stable caregiver to maintain his regimen of prescription food, joint supplements, and possible surgery with physical therapy.  He will be worth EVERY penny.

In the video, you can see that he moves pretty well, but seldom puts full weight on his left hip.  

If you can't adopt Big Country, but would like to meet him, and make a donation toward his medical costs (x-rays alone were $1000), please come visit him at the Well Pet Clinic in Lexington Park on Saturday!

attributes.descriptionHtml: Bonita was rescued from a local animal shelter that does not adopt out Cane Corsos only euthanizes them if they end up there.  She was originally found as a stray and brought there.  She looks as though she was used to make someone lots of money making puppies and they did not bother to feed her to spend less and make even more money.  She is a quiet girl that I do not think has had alot of good attention from people.  But she is enjoying the attention she gets now from her foster parents and is looking forward to more  from her permanent home.  When she was rescued she had two growths on her head.  Our vet did a check on them and found that they were a result of repetitive trauma.  These lumps should eventually dissapate but it will take some time.  She is looking better already with a steady diet of good food and the love she is getting.  If you are able to give her a permanent loving home please come meet her on our adoption day.
